        "assistant": "“**Off-token route**” and **embodied cognition** differ mainly in **what kind of thing they describe**.\n\n### Off-token route\n\nAn **off-token route** is an AI/software architecture idea.\n\nIt means some part of a system’s work happens **outside the model’s token-by-token language generation**.\n\nExample:\n\n- An LLM receives: “Book me a flight.”\n- Instead of only producing text, the system calls a flight-booking API.\n- The API call, database lookup, permission check, or tool execution is an **off-token route**.\n\nSo it is about **system routing and computation outside text tokens**.\n\n---\n\n### Embodied cognition\n\n**Embodied cognition** is a theory in cognitive science and philosophy of mind.\n\nIt says cognition is not just abstract symbol manipulation in the brain. Instead, thinking is deeply shaped by the body’s:\n\n- senses\n- motor abilities\n- physical environment\n- bodily feedback\n- action in the world\n\nExample:\n\n- You understand “grasping an idea” partly through bodily experience with grasping objects.\n- A robot learns better by physically interacting with objects, not just processing text descriptions.\n- Human spatial reasoning depends on vision, movement, balance, and bodily orientation.\n\nSo embodied cognition is about **how minds think through bodies and environments**.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Domain |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Off-token route** | A system process outside token-based language generation | AI/software architecture |\n| **Embodied cognition** | The idea that cognition depends on bodily experience and action | Cognitive science/philosophy |\n\n### Simple version\n\nAn **off-token route** is a technical pathway outside an AI model’s text-token stream.\n\n**Embodied cognition** is the idea that intelligence is grounded in bodily interaction with the world.\n\nThey can overlap in AI discussions: for example, a robot using sensors and motors may involve off-token routes for perception and action. But they are not the same thing. One is an **engineering mechanism**; the other is a **theory of cognition**.",
